cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.CR, cs.SI, cs.CC

The paper deals with information theoretic secure communication in a network with erasure channels and state feedback, which falls under the domain of information theory (cs.IT). The use of feedback and the consideration of intermediate nodes generating private randomness suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of networked systems (cs.NI). The presence of eavesdropping channels and the focus on secrecy suggest that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of cryptography (cs.CR). The development of polynomial time algorithms suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the use of mathematical modeling and analysis suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of systems and control (cs.SI).
